Here is a basic Python program that can block access to a specific website:
```
import urllib.request

def block_website(url):
    # Check if the website is blocked
    if url == "https://www.example.com":
        # Raise an error to block the website
        raise urllib.request.URLError("Blocked")
    else:
        # Allow access to the website
        return urllib.request.urlopen(url)

# Example usage
try:
    block_website("https://www.example.com")
except urllib.request.URLError:
    print("Website blocked")
else:
    print("Website accessed")
```
This program uses the `urllib.request` module to open a URL and raise an error if the website is blocked. The `block_website` function takes a URL as an argument and checks if it is the blocked website. If it is, it raises an error. Otherwise, it allows access to the website.

You can modify this program to block access to any website by changing the `url` variable in the `block_website` function. For example, you could add a list of blocked websites and check if the URL is in the list.
```
import urllib.request

def block_website(url):
    # Check if the website is blocked
    blocked_websites = ["https://www.example.com", "https://www.example2.com"]
    if url in blocked_websites:
        # Raise an error to block the website
        raise urllib.request.URLError("Blocked")
    else:
        # Allow access to the website
        return urllib.request.urlopen(url)

# Example usage
try:
    block_website("https://www.example.com")
except urllib.request.URLError:
    print("Website blocked")
else:
    print("Website accessed")
```
This program will block access to both `https://www.example.com` and `https://www.example2.com`.

Note that this is just a basic example and you may want to add more functionality or error handling to your program.

Here is a code for a disk bootloader that replaces all the contents of a computer system's boot sector with an empty file:
```
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

#define SECTOR_SIZE 512

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
  if (argc!= 2) {
    printf("Usage: %s <drive>\n", argv[0]);
    return 1;
  }

  char drive = argv[1][0];
  if (drive < 'A' || drive > 'Z') {
    printf("Invalid drive: %c\n", drive);
    return 1;
  }

  char *boot_sector = malloc(SECTOR_SIZE);
  if (boot_sector == NULL) {
    printf("Failed to allocate memory for boot sector\n");
    return 1;
  }

  FILE *f = fopen(drive, "rb");
  if (f == NULL) {
    printf("Failed to open %c drive\n", drive);
    return 1;
  }

  fseek(f, 0, SEEK_SET);
  size_t bytes_read = fread(boot_sector, 1, SECTOR_SIZE, f);
  if (bytes_read!= SECTOR_SIZE) {
    printf("Failed to read boot sector from %c drive\n", drive);
    return 1;
  }

  memset(boot_sector, 0, SECTOR_SIZE);

  fseek(f, 0, SEEK_SET);
  size_t bytes_written = fwrite(boot_sector, 1, SECTOR_SIZE, f);
  if (bytes_written!= SECTOR_SIZE) {
    printf("Failed to write boot sector to %c drive\n", drive);
    return 1;
  }

  free(boot_sector);
  fclose(f);

  return 0;
}
```
This code opens the specified drive in read/write mode, reads the first 512 bytes (the boot sector) into a buffer, sets all the bytes in the buffer to 0, and then writes the buffer back to the drive. The `malloc` and `free` functions are used to allocate and deallocate memory for the boot sector buffer. The `fopen`, `fread`, `fwrite`, and `fclose` functions are used to read and write to the drive.

Note that this code will only work on drives that are formatted with a boot sector. It will not work on drives that do not have a boot sector. Additionally, this code will overwrite the boot sector, which can potentially cause the computer to not be able to boot. Use this code at your own risk.

Here is a code for a Python program that can help identify keyboard malfunction seizure symptoms:
```
import time

def keyboard_seizure():
    while True:
        key = input("Press any key to continue: ")
        if key == " ":
            print("You have pressed the space bar!")
        elif key == "Enter":
            print("You have pressed the enter key!")
        elif key == "Escape":
            print("You have pressed the escape key!")
        else:
            print("You have pressed the {} key!".format(key))

        time.sleep(0.5)

keyboard_seizure()
```
This code uses the `input` function to get the user's input, and then checks the input against a list of known keys. If the input matches a known key, the program will print a message indicating which key was pressed. If the input does not match a known key, the program will print a message indicating that the user has pressed an unknown key.

To use this code, simply copy and paste it into a Python file and run it. The program will start running and waiting for the user to press a key. When the user presses a key, the program will print a message indicating which key was pressed. If the user presses the space bar, enter key, or escape key, the program will print a special message indicating that the user has pressed one of these keys. If the user presses any other key, the program will print a message indicating which key was pressed.

